Hey.

32
00:01:21,041 --> 00:01:23,000
Hi, sweet boy. How are you?

33
00:01:24,208 --> 00:01:26,041
I thought, um...
Hi.

34
00:01:26,083 --> 00:01:28,041
You weren't coming
till after work.

35
00:01:28,083 --> 00:01:30,500
Uh, yeah,
but Lucas got invited

36
00:01:30,542 --> 00:01:32,333
to this, um, puppy party
on Saturday,

37
00:01:32,375 --> 00:01:35,291
and I wanted to rsvp, and I
couldn't find the invitation.

38
00:01:35,333 --> 00:01:37,458
You left it on the refrigerator.
I already rsvp'd.

39
00:01:37,500 --> 00:01:39,250
Oh, thanks.

40
00:01:39,291 --> 00:01:41,083
Hey, Violet, uh,

41
00:01:41,125 --> 00:01:43,834
I want to... say something,

42
00:01:43,875 --> 00:01:47,041
and I-I need you to know that
I'm not trying to pick a fight.

43
00:01:49,083 --> 00:01:51,000
Okay.

44
00:01:52,500 --> 00:01:54,625
We really need
to stick to our plan.

45
00:01:54,667 --> 00:01:56,208
Which means?

46
00:01:56,250 --> 00:01:58,041
That if you have a problem
with an invitation,

47
00:01:58,083 --> 00:01:59,417
you call me up,
and we deal with it,

48
00:01:59,458 --> 00:02:01,041
but it's my time with Lucas,

49
00:02:01,083 --> 00:02:03,917
and you can't just,
you know, show up here.

50
00:02:03,959 --> 00:02:06,041
To my own house?

51
00:02:06,083 --> 00:02:08,750
To spend five minutes
with my son before work?

52
00:02:08,792 --> 00:02:09,750
We made a deal and--

53
00:02:09,792 --> 00:02:11,750
I know, I know, but...

54
00:02:11,792 --> 00:02:13,792
Does it seem like
it's working,

55
00:02:13,834 --> 00:02:15,542
moving back and forth

56
00:02:15,583 --> 00:02:17,083
between the house
and the hotel?

57
00:02:17,125 --> 00:02:19,542
I mean, don't--don't you feel
unsettled all the time?

58
00:02:19,583 --> 00:02:21,542
I do, but we
agreed that we would try

59
00:02:21,583 --> 00:02:23,542
to make this transition
as seamless as possible

60
00:02:23,583 --> 00:02:25,250
for Lucas, so--
I know, I know,

61
00:02:25,291 --> 00:02:27,166
but if it's driving us crazy,
he's gonna sense it.

62
00:02:27,208 --> 00:02:29,083
Okay,
what do you suggest?

63
00:02:29,125 --> 00:02:31,542
Well, I think a better idea
would be for me

64
00:02:31,583 --> 00:02:33,458
to move back in here
full-time

65
00:02:33,500 --> 00:02:36,000
and for you to find
a place nearby.

66
00:02:38,667 --> 00:02:40,625
Well, it's your house.

67
00:02:40,667 --> 00:02:42,750
Well, just think about it.

68
00:02:42,792 --> 00:02:44,000
Okay?

69
00:02:45,583 --> 00:02:47,041
All right.

70
00:02:47,083 --> 00:02:48,917
Mommy loves you.

71
00:02:50,083 --> 00:02:51,583
I'll see you tonight,
okay?

72
00:02:57,000 --> 00:02:59,000
Okay, bud.

73
00:02:59,041 --> 00:03:00,333
What's that?
That's coffee.

74
00:03:00,375 --> 00:03:02,542
What's that?
Oh, that's a peach.

75
00:03:02,583 --> 00:03:05,917
Kendra and I have been
together for six years.

76
00:03:05,959 --> 00:03:09,458
We're ready, really ready,
to have children of our own.

77
00:03:09,500 --> 00:03:12,458
And, Evan, I'm guessing
we'll be using your sperm?

78
00:03:12,500 --> 00:03:14,542
It's the neighborly thing
to do.

79
00:03:14,583 --> 00:03:17,250
So, uh, which one of you
is going to carry the baby?

80
00:03:17,291 --> 00:03:18,667
I will.

81
00:03:18,709 --> 00:03:20,000
And we'll use my egg.

82
00:03:20,041 --> 00:03:22,333
That way we can both be
a part of the experience.

83
00:03:22,375 --> 00:03:24,792
Okay. Well, I'll need
to examine you both.

84
00:03:24,834 --> 00:03:26,750
And, uh, I also think
it's a good idea

85
00:03:26,792 --> 00:03:30,041
if the three of you sit down
with one of our therapists.

86
00:03:30,083 --> 00:03:31,333
Why?

87
00:03:31,375 --> 00:03:33,875
Well, Evan isn't just
an anonymous sperm donor.

88
00:03:33,917 --> 00:03:35,041
He's obviously a part
of your lives,

89
00:03:35,083 --> 00:03:37,667
and presumably
will continue to be, right?

90
00:03:37,709 --> 00:03:39,041
But isn't that better?

91
00:03:39,083 --> 00:03:41,375
It's not about better
or worse.

92
00:03:41,417 --> 00:03:44,000
It's about a situation that has
some potential complications.

93
00:03:44,041 --> 00:03:46,458
The three of you are all going
to be involved in the pregnancy

94
00:03:46,500 --> 00:03:48,709
and to some extent,
the child rearing.

95
00:03:48,750 --> 00:03:51,041
I just want you to go into this
knowing what the stress points

96
00:03:51,083 --> 00:03:53,834
are going to be
in an arrangement like this.

97
00:03:53,875 --> 00:03:55,166
We appreciate that,
Dr. Reilly.

98
00:03:55,208 --> 00:03:56,375
We do--

99
00:03:56,417 --> 00:03:57,583
we can handle anything.

100
00:03:57,625 --> 00:03:59,291
Whatever happens,
we'll work it out.

101
00:03:59,333 --> 00:04:02,041
And a therapist will give you
a running start.

102
00:04:02,083 --> 00:04:03,083
Dr. Reilly--

103
00:04:03,125 --> 00:04:04,291
guys, I'm not
trying to make you

104
00:04:04,333 --> 00:04:05,500
jump through hoops here.

105
00:04:05,542 --> 00:04:07,917
I really think this will
help you as parents.

106
00:04:07,959 --> 00:04:10,041
I'm also not asking.

107
00:04:12,083 --> 00:04:14,625
Cleaning supplies
secured under the sink?

108
00:04:14,667 --> 00:04:17,333
Yes, all of the cabinets
in the house are secure.

109
00:04:17,375 --> 00:04:19,417
You know where
the fire detector is?

110
00:04:19,458 --> 00:04:20,959
Yep, right there
above the bed.

111
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:22,959
Okay, you'll need
to test that monthly.

112
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:24,834
Change the batteries
once a year.

113
00:04:24,875 --> 00:04:26,834
I have a reminder
set in my calendar.

114
00:04:26,875 --> 00:04:29,208
Also,
I have made sure to, uh,

115
00:04:29,250 --> 00:04:32,959
secure all of the balcony doors
with child-proof locks.

116
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:35,250
Good. Good.

117
00:04:35,291 --> 00:04:38,041
How do you plan on dealing
with the drowning hazard

118
00:04:38,083 --> 00:04:40,041
the ocean presents?

119
00:04:40,083 --> 00:04:42,625
Oh, uh...

120
00:04:42,667 --> 00:04:46,041
I can't imagine ever letting
that baby out of my arms,

121
00:04:46,083 --> 00:04:48,000
but, uh, if I do,

122
00:04:48,041 --> 00:04:51,125
I will not let her or him
go outside.

123
00:04:51,166 --> 00:04:53,125
I mean, the sun
is not our friend.

124
00:04:53,166 --> 00:04:55,291
I don't know if you know
how many, uh,

125
00:04:55,333 --> 00:04:58,250
cases of skin cancer are
reported each year, but...

126
00:04:58,291 --> 00:05:02,500
Well, the sun is a bit
beyond my purview.

127
00:05:05,750 --> 00:05:09,375
That was a joke, right?

128
00:05:09,417 --> 00:05:11,166
What?

129
00:05:16,500 --> 00:05:19,750
Is there a man living here
you neglected to tell me about?

130
00:05:30,125 --> 00:05:33,000
You sure you don't want me
to carry it?

131
00:05:33,041 --> 00:05:34,083
I got it.

132
00:05:34,125 --> 00:05:35,583
Okay.

133
00:05:35,625 --> 00:05:36,959
Ooh!

134
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:38,083
What are these again?

135
00:05:38,125 --> 00:05:39,917
I seriously can't believe

136
00:05:39,959 --> 00:05:41,792
you've never heard
of tinkertoys.

137
00:05:41,834 --> 00:05:43,041
I spent,
like, half my childhood

138
00:05:43,083 --> 00:05:45,000
building forts
and castles to play in.

139
00:05:45,041 --> 00:05:46,834
You're gonna love it.

140
00:05:46,875 --> 00:05:48,208
Oh, can we get these, too?

141
00:05:48,250 --> 00:05:49,834
Why do you want to play
with cards?

142
00:05:49,875 --> 00:05:51,041
We could build stuff.

143
00:05:51,083 --> 00:05:53,083
Please, dad.

144
00:05:53,125 --> 00:05:55,583
Maybe next time, okay?

145
00:06:01,917 --> 00:06:04,000
I'll meet you outside, dad.

146
00:06:06,083 --> 00:06:08,125
Can you add a pack of cards
to that, too, please?

147
00:06:09,375 --> 00:06:11,333
So, Evan, how do you
see your role

148
00:06:11,375 --> 00:06:12,542
in this baby's life?

149
00:06:12,583 --> 00:06:14,125
Donate the sperm,
build the crib,

150
00:06:14,166 --> 00:06:16,834
and then I just kind of
want to be the fun uncle--

151
00:06:16,875 --> 00:06:18,875
water fights
and movie nights,

152
00:06:18,917 --> 00:06:20,125
no diapers.

153
00:06:20,166 --> 00:06:22,125
Which is great, because I'll
be home with the baby.

154
00:06:22,166 --> 00:06:23,333
Rosie works, so...

155
00:06:23,375 --> 00:06:25,750
And those roles
are great for now,

156
00:06:25,792 --> 00:06:28,041
but as a baby grows,
things do change.

157
00:06:28,083 --> 00:06:31,000
Problems come up,
arguments happen,

158
00:06:31,041 --> 00:06:33,834
and if Evan disagrees with
any of your parenting choices,

159
00:06:33,875 --> 00:06:36,208
he would,
as the biological father,

160
00:06:36,250 --> 00:06:37,625
have legal standing

161
00:06:37,667 --> 00:06:39,041
unless you
specify otherwise now.

162
00:06:39,083 --> 00:06:40,166
Like in a contract?

163
00:06:40,208 --> 00:06:42,166
Yeah. Well,
in most situations,

164
00:06:42,208 --> 00:06:43,417
a contract
is not a bad idea.

165
00:06:43,458 --> 00:06:45,000
What would it say,

166
00:06:45,041 --> 00:06:47,041
that I don't have any right
to be involved with the baby?

167
00:06:47,083 --> 00:06:48,166
It can say
whatever you want.

168
00:06:48,208 --> 00:06:50,166
It's just a formality.

169
00:06:50,208 --> 00:06:52,667
But that feels so...
Business-like

170
00:06:52,709 --> 00:06:55,166
and this is not
a business decision.

171
00:06:55,208 --> 00:06:57,375
No, but if it's what
people normally do--

172
00:06:57,417 --> 00:07:00,041
we're having a baby, Rose,
not closing a deal.

173
00:07:00,083 --> 00:07:01,834
Yeah, I agree
with Kendra.

174
00:07:01,875 --> 00:07:03,875
It feels impersonal.

175
00:07:03,917 --> 00:07:05,834
R-Rose,

176
00:07:05,875 --> 00:07:07,083
is there something you would
like to say to Evan?

177
00:07:07,125 --> 00:07:08,750
No, not right now.

178
00:07:08,792 --> 00:07:09,959
Come on, Rose.

179
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:11,041
We'll talk about it later.

180
00:07:11,083 --> 00:07:12,125
Rosie...

181
00:07:12,166 --> 00:07:13,625
Guys, I'm a therapist.

182
00:07:13,667 --> 00:07:16,500
There's very little that I
haven't seen or heard.

183
00:07:16,542 --> 00:07:19,208
And this is not a place
of judgment.

184
00:07:19,250 --> 00:07:21,083
But getting what you want

185
00:07:21,125 --> 00:07:23,667
has to start
with the truth.

186
00:07:23,709 --> 00:07:25,125
So...

187
00:07:29,250 --> 00:07:31,667
We're in love.

188
00:07:31,709 --> 00:07:33,500
Okay.

189
00:07:33,542 --> 00:07:36,000
We're...

190
00:07:36,041 --> 00:07:38,125
All in love.

191
00:07:44,625 --> 00:07:46,041
Whatcha doin'?

192
00:07:46,083 --> 00:07:47,125
Oh, I'm just trying

193
00:07:47,166 --> 00:07:49,125
to maximize my ten minutes
between patients.

194
00:07:49,166 --> 00:07:52,041
I got kinda
jammed up today.

195
00:07:52,083 --> 00:07:53,500
Feel like taking a break
at lunch

196
00:07:53,542 --> 00:07:55,166
for pizza and pins?

197
00:07:55,208 --> 00:07:56,750
Greasy slices,

198
00:07:56,792 --> 00:07:58,500
slippery bowling balls,
my treat.

199
00:07:58,542 --> 00:08:00,667
Well, that sounds like fun,
but I don't know

200
00:08:00,709 --> 00:08:02,792
if my digestive track
could handle it,

201
00:08:02,834 --> 00:08:05,041
plus, uh...
I hate putting on shoes

202
00:08:05,083 --> 00:08:08,000
that a hundred other people
have worn before me, you know--

203
00:08:08,041 --> 00:08:09,417
oh, come on.
It'll be fun.

204
00:08:09,458 --> 00:08:12,083
I'll even buy
the pepto and purell.

205
00:08:12,125 --> 00:08:15,000
Thanks, but, uh...
Maybe some other time.

206
00:08:19,458 --> 00:08:21,583
Hey. I was
just looking for you.

207
00:08:21,625 --> 00:08:23,291
And now you found me.

208
00:08:23,333 --> 00:08:24,500
You busy today?

209
00:08:24,542 --> 00:08:26,041
I'm pretty much
caught up on my charts.

210
00:08:26,083 --> 00:08:27,500
A couple of patients
are coming in--

211
00:08:27,542 --> 00:08:29,834
are you ready
to cut again?

212
00:08:29,875 --> 00:08:31,291
A patient with
an obstructive neurosarcoid

213
00:08:31,333 --> 00:08:33,083
was scheduled
for this afternoon,

214
00:08:33,125 --> 00:08:35,041
but buddle's coming off
an all-nighter,

215
00:08:35,083 --> 00:08:37,041
and I need someone.

216
00:08:37,083 --> 00:08:38,625
Well, I thought I might
assist a few before i--

217
00:08:38,667 --> 00:08:40,208
either you're ready to come
back to the hospital and work

218
00:08:40,250 --> 00:08:41,667
or you're not.

219
00:08:43,625 --> 00:08:46,000
I'm ready.

220
00:08:46,041 --> 00:08:47,750
I'm definitely ready.

221
00:08:47,792 --> 00:08:49,000
Good.

222
00:08:54,417 --> 00:08:56,041
We know it sounds crazy.

223
00:08:56,083 --> 00:08:58,000
I understand being in love.
I'm not judging.

224
00:08:58,041 --> 00:08:59,750
You are.
Everyone judges us.

225
00:08:59,792 --> 00:09:02,750
But we appreciate how hard
you're trying not to.

226
00:09:02,792 --> 00:09:04,166
Okay.

227
00:09:04,208 --> 00:09:06,667
Well, tell me
about yourselves.

228
00:09:06,709 --> 00:09:08,166
The first night was...

229
00:09:08,208 --> 00:09:09,458
It was amazing.

230
00:09:09,500 --> 00:09:10,959
The first night
usually is.

231
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:12,041
But so was the next morning.

232
00:09:12,083 --> 00:09:13,792
And every morning
after that.

233
00:09:13,834 --> 00:09:14,875
Most mornings.

234
00:09:14,917 --> 00:09:16,417
It--it sounds very easy.

235
00:09:16,458 --> 00:09:18,375
It's not.
We have rules.

236
00:09:18,417 --> 00:09:20,625
Every decision
has to be unanimous.

237
00:09:20,667 --> 00:09:22,000
We have to avoid
the two against one

238
00:09:22,041 --> 00:09:24,083
so no one feels
ganged up on.
Okay.

239
00:09:24,125 --> 00:09:26,041
Y-You are
talking about things

240
00:09:26,083 --> 00:09:29,041
that are in the context
of the relationship.

241
00:09:29,083 --> 00:09:31,250
But there is a world
out there,

242
00:09:31,291 --> 00:09:34,083
the world that you would be
raising your child in.

243
00:09:34,125 --> 00:09:36,250
And that world
is not quite as accepting

244
00:09:36,291 --> 00:09:37,500
about things
that don't appear--

245
00:09:37,542 --> 00:09:39,500
normal?

246
00:09:39,542 --> 00:09:42,166
I come from a home where there
wasn't a lot of love.

247
00:09:42,208 --> 00:09:44,250
There was a lot of...

248
00:09:44,291 --> 00:09:45,458
Commitment--

249
00:09:45,500 --> 00:09:47,291
35 years of marriage--

250
00:09:47,333 --> 00:09:49,542
and a lot of what people
call normal,

251
00:09:49,583 --> 00:09:51,417
but not much love.

252
00:09:51,458 --> 00:09:54,000
Kendra and Rose and me...

253
00:09:57,667 --> 00:10:00,000
There's a lot of love here.

254
00:10:02,083 --> 00:10:03,041
A-A what?

255
00:10:03,083 --> 00:10:04,417
A polyamorous triad.

256
00:10:04,458 --> 00:10:06,458
Three people in a committed,
monogamous relationship.

257
00:10:06,500 --> 00:10:08,041
I can barely keep up
with one partner.

258
00:10:08,083 --> 00:10:09,625
I can't imagine
trying to satisfy two.

259
00:10:09,667 --> 00:10:11,834
There's no way that works.

260
00:10:11,875 --> 00:10:13,083
Every couple, or triad,
is different.

261
00:10:13,125 --> 00:10:14,667
You know,
you can't generalize.

262
